{
  "answer": "**The work is *Andreas* by Cynewulf, Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis Old English poem stages a dialogue at sea between the apostle Andreas (Andrew) and the disguised Christ (the \"Lord of glory\"), who appears as the helmsman of a ship. Andreas praises the helmsman for his extraordinary skill in navigating the vessel through a storm, without yet recognizing his divine identity. The saint notes his own seafaring experience (\"sixteen times on a sea-boat\"), marvels at the ship's speed (\"fares, foam-necked, most like a fowl\"), and highlights the helmsman's youth (\"young ... not old in winters\") despite his masterful command as a \"wave-rider.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-ca9772).",
